            <section id="history">
                <h2>Background</h2>
                <h3>History</h3>
                <text> Beginning in 1978/1979, the President’s Ambassadors at St. Mary’s University have demonstrated high levels of leadership and dedication to the university mission and Marianist Charism. 
                The Ambassadors are a direct representation of the Office of the President as well as the student body. Together these leaders preserve campus traditions, serve as model student-leaders, animate 
                the Charism, and represent the university across campus and the greater San Antonio community.
                </text><br><br>
                <h3>St. Mary’s University President’s Ambassadors Mission</h3>
                <text>Through the principles of Servant-Leadership, Professionalism and Hospitality, the mission of the President’s Ambassadors is to represent the President and university at St. Mary's at 
                special events, to promote the vast successes and advancements of the University, and to communicate through all that we do, the virtue of our beloved Marianist heritage.
                </text>  <br> <br>
                <h3>Understanding the Organization and its Mission</h3>
                <text>The President’s Ambassadors are students whose dedication to the mission and advancement of St. Mary’s is expressed through their leadership, service, and hospitality on behalf of the
                President at University events.
                </text><br>   <br>
                <text>Symbolizing the rich cultural, geographic and academic diversity of the student body, the President's Ambassadors perform an essential function in promoting the University by 
                creating positive impressions and by sharing with guests the values and traditions of St. Mary’s.
                </text><br><br>
                <text> As the “public face of the University,” Ambassadors are entrusted with maintaining and promoting the St. Mary’s reputation for quality education, commitment to service, Catholic
                and Marianist identity and mission.
                </text> 
                <text>St. Mary’s University, as a Catholic Marianist University, fosters the formation of people in faith and educates leaders for the common good through community, integrated liberal 
                arts and professional education, and academic excellence.
                </text><br><br>
                <text>While professionalism, leadership, and hospitality are essential for effective service as an Ambassador, it is also important to understand that which sets St. Mary’s apart, 
                a sense of community and family spirit. This treasured characteristic of Marianist institutions perseveres on our campus and is a part of the St. Mary’s culture.
                </text><br><br>
                <text>Historically, contemplation of the dispositions of Mary, our patroness, has tended to give a certain ambiance to the Marianist communities. One time-honored term given to this
                way of being is “family spirit.” It is often referred to as some “indefinable something” which is nonetheless noticeable, and which makes it comfortable to be in a Marianist community. 
                Since one of the prime expressions of “family spirit” lies in the sense of community and mutual interdependence and respect which should pervade our enterprise and make ours observably different from other institutions
                </text> 
            </section>

            <section id="mission">
                <h2>Mission</h2>
                <p>St. Mary’s University, as a Catholic Marianist University, fosters the formation of people in faith and educates leaders for the common good through community, 
                integrated liberal arts and professional education, and academic excellence.</p><br>
                <p>The St. Mary’s University mission statement is a reflection of the Characteristics of Marianist Universities. There are five elements that characterize
                the Marianist approach to education:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Educate for formation in faith</li>
                        <li>Provide an integral quality education</li>
                        <li>Educate in the family spirit</li>
                        <li>Educate for service, justice and peace, and integrity of creation</li>
                        <li>Educate for adaptation and change</li>
                    </ul>
            </section>

